ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;"><strong><em>John Heilemann</em></strong><strong>: Trump is constantly t=
esting the
boundary of what executive authority is versus what the legislative branch =
was intended to have in its purview. What are your thoughts on all this?</s=
trong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><em>Brian</em> <em>Schatz</em>: I think there=E2=
=80=99s an unholy alliance between Trump=E2=80=99s basic instinct to just p=
ress boundaries, break rules, and push people around, and now there=E2=80=
=99s a kind of underlying legal theory that is trying to white-shoe-law-fir=
m-up
his authoritarian tendencies. I think that=E2=80=99s the balance someone li=
ke me has to strike. We have to separate out those things where he=E2=80=99=
s just trying to wish a political problem away [from] where he can do real =
harm. Because of his federal funding freeze, portals were shut down, housin=
g projects were stopped, loans were stopped, and all the rest of it. That=
=E2=80=99s real harm, and we had to intervene. Whereas, some of this other =
stuff is just like, he=E2=80=99s using executive orders as a substitute for=
 a tweet.
And in those instances, I think we have to monitor them, but not overreact.=
</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0=
;margin-bottom:0px;">On both the right and the left, there=E2=80=99s this t=
endency to think of [Trump] as all-powerful. Online, people are like, <em>W=
ell, it=E2=80=99s all moot because the Supreme Court is bought</em>. I=E2=
=80=99m not pleased with the Supreme Court at all=E2=80=94and I do think we=
=E2=80=99re gonna get some adverse opinions=E2=80=94but they talk about <em=
>not </em>obeying in advance,
and that goes for the left, too. We=E2=80=99ve still got leverage. The fili=
buster still exists. These statutes still exist. We still have some Republi=
can colleagues who are going to, at least quietly, push back when it comes =
to their prerogatives. So I just think it=E2=80=99s very important for peop=
le on the left to not assume that this guy just writes something down and i=
t=E2=80=99s now the law of the land. Part of what we have to do is sort out=
 how much of this is just talking, and how much of this is, <em>Oh, he=E2=
=80=99s
doing it</em>. For example, on tariffs, he=E2=80=99s got pretty unambiguous=
 authority to just raise our prices by next week. So that=E2=80=99s real st=
uff. But him yammering about Greenland=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99s not happening.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;=
margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>A lot of Democrats have viewed the O.M.B. memo =
being rescinded as the first win of Trump 2.0. JB Pritzker said the pressur=
e from governors and people outside is what led them to have to climb down.=
 Do you see
it that way? Does this point the direction toward how Democrats should go a=
bout taking on Trump in this new term?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;mar=
gin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Firstly=
, yes, I think this was a minor victory, but it=E2=80=99s going to be a lon=
g battle, specifically on the question of federal spending. Politically, we=
 have a long road to travel, and so this is not like, <em>Hey, we had a gre=
at week, good job, everybody.</em> But it=E2=80=99s important to
remember that we are out of power, but we are not powerless. We have tools =
in our toolkit, and we have to start using them. I do think we were so shel=
l shocked by the loss, and=E2=80=94in my view, appropriately=E2=80=94not ru=
nning back into the same fight with the same playbook, that there was a lit=
tle bit of, <em>What the hell, what=E2=80=99s the plan?</em></p><p style=3D=
"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">I understand=
 the frustration. The easiest thing in the world would have been to rev up =
the
outrage machine, and that=E2=80=99s a recipe for only once in a while being=
 the majority party in Congress and in the presidency. So we=E2=80=99ve got=
 to do some thinking about how to reconstitute the Democratic Party.</p></d=
iv>
