reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"><div style=
=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;=
;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:150%;text-al=
ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;"><strong>Is this more a moment for Democrats to be rethinking their ideo=
logical
orientation regarding what they believe, or is this a moment to be focused =
on thinking about tactical, strategic messaging changes?</strong></p><p sty=
le=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bo=
ttom:0px;">We lost a bunch of people who are nominally liberal, who voted f=
or Donald Trump. There was something in the water culturally that didn=E2=
=80=99t have to do with where we are on the right-left spectrum. I want to =
recognize that was part of the problem. My own view is that
people were very, very pissed off at inflation. People were very, very piss=
ed off at having an old president who didn=E2=80=99t look like he was up to=
 it. And we could shake off some of that with <strong>Kamala Harris</strong=
> running a vigorous=E2=80=94and, in my view, excellent=E2=80=94campaign, b=
ut we couldn=E2=80=99t shake off <em>all</em> of it.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">I =
think, ideologically, on questions of immigration and the border, we should=
 go back to
home, which is not to accept cruelty to immigrants as the Democratic Party =
position, but to just get across that we believe in order. On immigration, =
we do need to shift back to the Obama/Clinton view. I don=E2=80=99t think t=
hat=E2=80=99s true across the board.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-b=
ottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">For the peop=
le who=E2=80=99ve expressed this newfound sympathy toward the Republican Pa=
rty, the main objection they had to Democrats was they just couldn=E2=80=99=
t see
<strong>Joe Biden</strong> serving another four years and being capable. At=
 least Donald Trump looked vigorous. He=E2=80=99s only two years younger th=
an Joe Biden, but he=E2=80=99s wrong and strong. He looks like he=E2=80=99s=
 in charge of things, even if he=E2=80=99s <em>incompetently</em> in charge=
 of things. So I think our next nominee ought to be from the next generatio=
n. I don=E2=80=99t know if that=E2=80=99s someone in their forties, fifties=
, or sixties=E2=80=94but I do think that we are ready for a generational sh=
ift.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:
0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><s=
trong>The Bulwark=E2=80=99s Jonathan V. Last recently argued that the Supre=
me Court is now the only institution that can check Donald Trump=E2=80=94bu=
t at least two votes there will support anything he wants to do, and the co=
urt has already granted him blanket criminal immunity for official acts. So=
, he points out, =E2=80=9Cany meaningful check on Trump will require the pa=
rticipation of a large number of elected or appointed Republicans who have
not taken sides against Trump en masse for nearly a decade.=E2=80=9D And hi=
s question is, look at the system and tell me why it won=E2=80=99t produce =
the kind of outcome we would see in Belarus. Is that catastrophizing?</stro=
ng></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;margin-bottom:0px;">I think it=E2=80=99s both catastrophizing and poten=
tially true. There=E2=80=99s something in between =E2=80=9Ceverything is go=
ing to be okay=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re all cooked,=E2=80=9D and=
 that=E2=80=99s where we should all live. Democracy is not
what we have, it=E2=80=99s what we do. The separate and coequal branches of=
 government are not inert constitutional provisions. They=E2=80=99re about =
exercising power. And I think that wins beget wins, and losses beget losses=
=2E People are desperate and terrified.=
 And I understand that point of view.=20=
But we have to not presume we are powerless. Like it or not, the filibuster=
 is still in place. So if Donald Trump doesn=E2=80=99t like one of these la=
ws, he can=E2=80=99t waive it by executive order; he=E2=80=99s got to come =
back to us. If
he wants a federal spending bill, he=E2=80=99s gotta come back to us. If he=
 wants to waive any of the provisions of <em>any </em>statute, he has to co=
me back to us. And look, I think the courts are going to back him when it=
=E2=80=99s close, but we have to remember, some of the things that he=E2=80=
=99s doing are <em>not </em>close. I don=E2=80=99t think he=E2=80=99s going=
 to get rid of birthright citizenship because the constitutional language i=
s absolutely plain.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><=
p style=3D"margin:0;">
All I would say is that if we=E2=80=99re going to win this, everybody has t=
o live somewhere in between =E2=80=9Cwe are cooked=E2=80=9D <em>and</em> =
=E2=80=9Cwe are going to be just fine.=E2=80=9D But we have to be vigilant.=
 We have to work together. We have to kick ass. And as my old friend, the f=
ormer Speaker of the Hawaii House of Representatives <strong>Calvin Say</st=
rong>, used to say: Be like the bamboo=E2=80=94bend, but don=E2=80=99t brea=
k.</p></div>
